'''Malaise''' ({{IPAc-en|m|ə|ˈ|l|eɪ|z}} {{respell|mə|LAYZ}}) is a feeling of general [[suffering|discomfort]], uneasiness or pain, often the first indication of an [[infection]] or other disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://medlineplus.gov/ency/article/003089.htm|title=Malaise: MedlinePlus Medical Encyclopedia|author=|date=|website=medlineplus.gov|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160916154928/https://medlineplus.gov/ency/article/003089.htm|archivedate=2016-09-16|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/section/well|title=Well|author=|date=|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180424040459/https://www.nytimes.com/section/well|archivedate=2018-04-24|df=}}</ref> The word has existed in the French language since at least the 12th century.

The term is also often used figuratively in other contexts; for example, "[[economic malaise]]" refers to an economy that is stagnant or in recession (compare [[Depression (economics)|depression]]). The term is particularly associated with the US [[1973–75 recession]].<ref>One example can be found in ''The Next 200 Years: A Scenario for America and the World'', by [[Herman Kahn]] et al., published in 1976, p. 2.</ref> A speech made by President [[Jimmy Carter]] in 1979 is commonly referred to as the [[Malaise speech|"malaise" speech]], although the term was not in the speech.

== Cause ==
Malaise is a [[non-specific symptom]] and can be present in the slightest ailment, such as an [[emotion]] (causing fainting, a [[vasovagal response]]) or hunger (light [[hypoglycemia]]<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://care.diabetesjournals.org/content/26/2/390|title=Short-Term, Delayed, and Working Memory Are Impaired During Hypoglycemia in Individuals With Type 1 Diabetes|first1=Andrew J.|last1=Sommerfield|first2=Ian J.|last2=Deary|first3=Vincent|last3=McAulay|first4=Brian M.|last4=Frier|date=1 February 2003|publisher=|journal=Diabetes Care|volume=26|issue=2|pages=390–396|via=care.diabetesjournals.org|doi=10.2337/diacare.26.2.390|pmid=12547868|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160913150624/http://care.diabetesjournals.org/content/26/2/390|archivedate=13 September 2016|df=}}</ref>), to the most serious conditions ([[cancer]], [[stroke]], [[heart attack]], [[internal bleeding]], etc.).

Malaise expresses a patient's uneasiness that "something is not right" that may need a medical examination to determine the significance.

Malaise is thought to be caused by the activation of an immune response, and the associated pro-inflammatory [[cytokines]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Dantzer|first1=Robert|title=Cytokine, Sickness Behavior, and Depression|journal=Immunology and allergy clinics of North America|date=1 December 2016|volume=29|issue=2|pages=247–264|doi=10.1016/j.iac.2009.02.002|pmc=2740752|issn=0889-8561|pmid=19389580}}</ref>

